FM Spokesman on DPRK's Stand on Nuclear Freeze and Way of Verification 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 14 (KCNA) -- A spokesman for the DPRK Foreign Ministry gave the following answer to a question put by KCNA Wednesday as regards the misinformation floated by some members of the international community about the objects to be frozen and the way of verification after the DPRK elaborated on the proposal on "reward for freeze" at the third round of the six-party talks:
 As already reported, all participants in the six-party talks except the U.S. expressed positive understanding and sympathy with the flexible proposal the DPRK made as the first-phase measure for a package solution based on simultaneous actions at the talks. They expressed their willingness to participate in implementing the proposal for reward for freeze and even the broad world public fairly assessed the DPRK's constructive stand for the solution of the nuclear issue. 
 The DPRK, however, is compelled to be vigilant against some forces misinterpreting the DPRK's stand in a bid to build up public opinion swimming against this international trend. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They assert that the DPRK's nuclear activities for a peaceful purpose are possible only after its return to NPT and under its regular cooperation with the IAEA and that even the DPRK side expressed understanding of this. They also claim that the DPRK has the stand of agreeing to the multi-party inspection i.e. the six participant nations of the six-party talks, although it opposes the IAEA's inspection of its nuclear freeze. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK would like to reclarify its stand here. Its ultimate goal is to realize the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK will dismantle its nuclear weapons program only when conditions for it are created by the U.S. drop of its hostile policy toward the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 To this end, it wishes to wipe out mistrust and build confidence between the DPRK and the U.S. by implementing the measure of "reward for freeze," to begin with. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK will naturally return to NPT if the Korean peninsula is denuclearized and those fundamental elements, which compelled the DPRK to pull out of the treaty, are consequently removed. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is the unshakable stand of the DPRK that it can not stop its nuclear activities for a peaceful purpose before this happens. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Its nuclear activities for a peaceful purpose are the issues pertaining to its sovereignty and this should never be included in the objects to be frozen or dismantled. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
It is a hard reality in the world that those countries outside NPT and those belonging to the nuclear-free zones are engaged in nuclear activities for peaceful purposes. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is, therefore, quite natural for the DPRK, a non-member country of NPT, to exercise such equal right even before its return to it and there is nothing strange about its nuclear activity for a peaceful purpose. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Clear is the stand of the DPRK on the issue of verification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 As already clarified by the DPRK, a freeze is the first phase leading to the final dismantlement of its nuclear program and the freeze is bound to be accompanied by an objective verification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 By verification the DPRK means monitoring the state of freeze. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The issue of inspection of the nuclear facilities and nuclear substance of the DPRK is something to be discussed only at the phase of dismantling its nuclear program. It is very illogical to argue about inspection from the phase of freeze. Moreover, any attempt to force the DPRK to accept it is nothing but a sinister attempt to disarm it. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Even after the third round of the six-party talks high-ranking officials of the U.S., in fact, do not hide their attempt to force the DPRK to "scrap its nuclear program first," asserting that they cannot make any reward unless the DPRK completely dismantles its nuclear program after halting its nuclear activity and accepting international inspection. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 It is quite preposterous for the U.S. to urge the DPRK to disarm itself before anything else under the present situation where the two countries are in a state of armistice and technically at war. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The DPRK, therefore, can never accept this.

Commemorative Functions Held Abroad 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 14 (KCNA) -- A joint seminar of political parties and organizations was held in Lima, Peru, on July 5 on the occasion of the tenth anniversary of the demise of President Kim Il Sung.
 Speeches were made by more than 10 personages including Genaro Ledesma Izquieta, chairman of the People's Front of Workers, Peasants and Students of Peru, Alberto Moreno, president of the New Left Movement of Peru, Luis Mateo Munoz, general secretary of the Socialist Party of Peru, and Tani Baler Lopera, chairman of the Peruvian Committee for Supporting the Independent and Peaceful Reunification of Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Highly praising the immortal exploits performed by Kim Il Sung, they said: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
The Peruvian people share with the world progressives the grief over the demise of    Kim Il Sung, the greatest man in the 20th century and the most prominent leader of the world working class. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They stressed that thanks to the wise guidance and noble sense of obligation of leader Kim Jong Il the revolutionary cause pioneered by Kim Il Sung has been successfully carried forward and the cause of perpetuating the memory of the President has been accomplished with success in Korea. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 They expressed full support and solidarity with the Korean people in their just cause. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A letter to Kim Jong Il was adopted at the seminar. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Seminars were held by the Revolutionary Socialist Party of Peru and the Peruvian Group for the Study of Kimilsungism on June 30 and 28. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Meanwhile, Korean film shows and photo exhibitions were held by the Mission of Tyumen Regional Administration in Moscow and a number of companies in India, Thailand, Iran and Singapore from July 2 to 5.

Withdrawal of Decision on Troop Dispatch to Iraq Demanded 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 14 (KCNA) -- The Democratic Workers' Party (DWP) of south Korea demanded the retraction of the plan for additional troop dispatch to Iraq and the withdrawal of the already dispatched troops from Iraq on July 11, according to KBS of south Korea.
 That day the deputy floor leader of the DWP referred to the fact that recently the U.S. Senate Intelligence Committee said the Iraqi war was launched on the basis of misinformation. He demanded the Bush administration make an apology to the UN and the international community for all distortions and frauds made by it as regards the Iraqi war. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Declaring the "motion on the troop dispatch" passed by the 16th National Assembly null and void, he stressed that NA must immediately deal with a "resolution on the reexamination of troop dispatch" and the "motion on the withdrawal of the decision on the troop dispatch" which have so far been put on hold. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He formally proposed NA's adoption of a resolution demanding the Bush administration make an apology for its start of the war of aggression against Iraq and pressure for troop dispatch.

Functions Held at DPRK Consulate General in Shenyang 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 14 (KCNA) -- Functions took place at the DPRK consulate general in Shenyang, China, on July 9 on the occasion of the 43rd anniversary of the DPRK-China Treaty of Friendship, Cooperation and Mutual Assistance.
 Present there on invitation were the vice-chairman of the Liaoning Provincial Political Consultative Conference of China, the deputy chief of the General Staff of the Liaoning Military Area of the Chinese People's Liberation Army, the vice-chairman of the Shenyang City Political Consultative Conference and other officials concerned. Consul General Rim Yong Phal and consuls of the DPRK were on hand. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The participants saw a DPRK film "The Great Leader Comrade Kim Jong Il Pays an Unofficial Visit to the People's Republic of China" and saw photos on the theme of his unofficial visit to China and on the Kumsusan Memorial Palace. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Then followed a reception. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp
 Speeches were made there.

Wu Bangguo Meets DPRK Military Delegation
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Beijing, July 13 (KCNA) -- Wu Bangguo, member of the Standing Committee of the Political Bureau of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China and chairman of the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress of China, Tuesday met and had a friendly talk with the DPRK military delegation led by Vice-Marshal Kim Il Chol, member of the DPRK National Defence Commission and minister of the People's Armed Forces, at the Great Hall of the People.
On hand were Colonel General Cao Gangchuan, member of the Political Bureau of the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China, vice-chairman of the Central Military Commission, state councilor and minister of Defence, and the chairman of the Foreign Affairs Committee of the National People's Congress of China, the deputy chief of the General Staff of the Chinese People's Liberation Army, and others. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The members of the delegation, DPRK ambassador to China Choe Jin Su, and the military attache of the DPRK embassy in Beijing were present. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Wu Bangguo stated that the party and the government of China highly valued the traditional friendship between China and the DPRK and that this friendship provided by the leaders of the old generation of the two countries was invariably gaining strength and developing. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The party, the government and the people of China regard it as a long-term policy and an important component of the external policy to develop the friendly relations with the DPRK and are making every possible effort to this end, he said. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The China visit of leader Kim Jong Il in April this year was an event of weighty importance in the development of the bilateral relations, Wu said, adding: During the visit the new collective leadership of China established relations of deep trust with him. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
The friendship between the two countries will steadily be consolidated as intended by Hu Jintao and Kim Jong Il, he said. 
He sincerely wished the Korean people greater achievements in various fields under the leadership of Kim Jong Il, manifesting positive support to the Korean people in their struggle to defend socialism and achieve the independent and peaceful reunification of the country.

Heritage Left by Kim Hyong Jik
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 14 (KCNA) -- The idea of Jiwon (Aim High), preparation for three contingencies, the idea of gaining comrades and two pistols - these are the heritage left to President Kim Il Sung by his father Kim Hyong Jik, an indomitable revolutionary fighter.
 The heritage is priceless treasure for the Korean revolution and an ideological source for the victory of the Juche revolutionary cause. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The President started his revolutionary activities with the revolutionary idea of Jiwon that one should fight generation after generation to achieve the liberation of the nation and with the mental preparation for three contingencies-- death from hunger, beating and cold. And he formed the Down-with-Imperialism Union (DIU) with the idea of gaining comrades, an organization which constituted the historical foundation of the Workers' Party of Korea, and started the Korean revolution with the two pistols. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Basing himself on the heritage, the President fathered the great Juche idea to pave the way of the Korean revolution, led the 20-year-long arduous anti-Japanese revolutionary struggle to victory to achieve the liberation of the country and successfully established the Korean-style socialist society centering around the popular masses in this land. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The heritage is now being carried forward by leader Kim Jong Il, who has pursued the unique Songun-based politics.

Young People Active for Scientific Development
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 14 (KCNA) -- In the Democratic People's Republic of Korea young scientists account for 76.5 percent of the holders of academic degrees and titles who play a pivotal role in the nation's scientific and technical development.
 Leader Kim Jong Il set forth the policy of giving importance to ideology, arms and science. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 With the whole society replete with the spirit of attaching a great importance to science and technology, young scientists have become a reliable backbone of the nation for the scientific and technological development. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A research team of young scientists has succeeded in somatic cell cloning of rabbits in a short span of time. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The KCC paduk programs developed by young scientists won the three consecutive World Championships, fully demonstrating the nation's software development. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In recent years alone, young scientists have scored wonderful achievements helpful towards the building of a great prosperous powerful nation. Among them are an architectural designing method for any streamline curved surface, a beer production method by using a new kind of refrigerant and solar battery made with local raw materials.

Implementation of June 15 Joint Declaration Called for
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 14 (KCNA) -- The June 15 North-South Joint Declaration is a signal post of hope for the Korean nation as it indicated a wide avenue for the Koreans whose life was full of twists and turns in last century to carve out their destiny by themselves. Rodong Sinmun Wednesday says this in a signed article.
 The article goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. aggression and high-handed practices are rampant in the world and the dark clouds of a war are gathering to hang over the Korean peninsula hour by hour owing to the U.S. imperialists, but the Korean nation is paving the way for reunification thanks to the joint declaration. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The road of national independence the nation is taking under the banner of the joint declaration leads to peaceful reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Originally the issue of Korea's reunification did not surface owing to the contradictions among Koreans but was forced upon them by foreign forces. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
There is no ground for Koreans to fight each other over the issue of reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. keen to dominate all the Koreans is to blame for the military confrontation and escalating tension on the Korean peninsula. National independence is the best option for saving the destiny of the Korean nation and a prerequisite to the peaceful reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The joint declaration calls for achieving reunification by federal formula, a goal to be attained by the Koreans themselves, opening a bright prospect of the peaceful reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The declaration underscores the need to work hard to achieve reunification by preserving the common points in the reunification proposals put forward by the north and the south to meet the nation's requirements and interests. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
It also makes it clear that the north and the south should develop national economy in a balanced manner through the economic cooperation between them and realize cooperation and exchange in all social fields to promote the bilateral confidence. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 From a realistic point of view achieving reunification by federal formula is the only way for the nation to solve the issue of the reunification of the country most smoothly and peacefully. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 In order to defend the peace of the country and the security of the nation all Koreans in the north, the south and overseas should unanimously support and uphold the Songun politics aimed to protect the destiny of the nation, the article concludes.
